   "source": [
    "# 26. What is Multicollinearity? Why Multicollinearity is Bad? How to detect and remove Multicollinearity?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6755ec25",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What is multicollinearity?\n",
    "Multicollinearity is a phenomena where two or more independent variables are highly correlated.\n",
    "In other words, one predictor variable can be used to be predic the value of another.\n",
    "This creates redundant information, skewing the results in a regression model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "cf14fb15",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "🔹 What is Multicollinearity?\n",
    "📌 Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "Multicollinearity occurs when:\n",
    "\n",
    "two or more independent variables are highly correlated with each other in a regression model.\n",
    "\n",
    "🧠 Intuition\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of giving unique information, features are repeating the same information.\n",
    "\n",
    "📊 Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Features:\n",
    "\n",
    "Height (cm)\n",
    "Height (inches)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 These are perfectly correlated ❌\n",
    "\n",
    "Another example:\n",
    "\n",
    "House size (sq ft)\n",
    "Number of rooms\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Strong correlation likely\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Why Multicollinearity is Bad?\n",
    "❌ 1. Unstable Coefficients\n",
    "Small data change → big change in coefficients\n",
    "Model becomes unreliable\n",
    "❌ 2. Hard to Interpret\n",
    "Cannot tell which feature is important\n",
    "Coefficients become misleading\n",
    "❌ 3. Inflated Variance\n",
    "Standard errors increase\n",
    "Confidence intervals become wide\n",
    "❌ 4. Affects Statistical Significance\n",
    "Important variables may appear insignificant\n",
    "❌ 5. Model Overfitting Risk\n",
    "Model learns redundant patterns\n",
    "🔹 Example Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose:\n",
    "\n",
    "Price=2×Size+3×Rooms\n",
    "\n",
    "If Size and Rooms are highly correlated:\n",
    "\n",
    "Model struggles to assign correct weights\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Coefficients may fluctuate randomly\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 How to Detect Multicollinearity?\n",
    "✅ 1. Correlation Matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "Check pairwise correlation:\n",
    "\n",
    "df.corr()\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 If correlation > 0.8 or 0.9 → problem\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 2. VIF (Variance Inflation Factor)\n",
    "\n",
    "Most important method ⭐\n",
    "\n",
    "VIF= 1/(1-R^2)\n",
    "\n",
    "Interpretation:\n",
    "VIF = 1 → no correlation\n",
    "VIF > 5 → moderate\n",
    "VIF > 10 → high multicollinearity\n",
    "✅ 3. Heatmap Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "Use heatmap to see correlations visually\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 4. High Standard Errors\n",
    "If coefficients have high standard errors → possible multicollinearity\n",
    "🔹 How to Remove Multicollinearity?\n",
    "✅ 1. Remove One of the Correlated Features\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Keep only one feature\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Keep height (cm), drop height (inches)\n",
    "✅ 2. Feature Selection\n",
    "Use domain knowledge\n",
    "Remove less important features\n",
    "✅ 3. PCA (Principal Component Analysis)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Convert correlated features into uncorrelated components\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 4. Regularization\n",
    "Use models like:\n",
    "Ridge Regression\n",
    "Lasso Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 These reduce coefficient instability\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 5. Combine Features\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Combine length + width → area\n",
    "🔹 Beginner-Friendly Version\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Multicollinearity means:\n",
    "\n",
    "features are too similar\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Problem:\n",
    "\n",
    "model gets confused\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Solution:\n",
    "\n",
    "remove or combine features\n",
    "🔹 Real-Life Analogy\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine:\n",
    "\n",
    "Two friends always give the same answer\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 You cannot tell who is contributing\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Interview Answer (5 lines)\n",
    "\n",
    "Multicollinearity occurs when independent variables in a regression model are highly correlated with each other. It causes instability in coefficient estimates, making the model difficult to interpret. It also increases variance and reduces statistical significance of features. It can be detected using correlation matrices and VIF scores. To handle it, we can remove correlated features, apply PCA, or use regularization techniques like Ridge or Lasso.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 One-Line Memory Trick\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Multicollinearity = features saying the same thing\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Pro Interview Tip\n",
    "\n",
    "You can add:\n",
    "\n",
    "“Multicollinearity does not affect prediction accuracy much but severely impacts interpretability.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Final Summary\n",
    "Highly correlated features → multicollinearity\n",
    "Causes unstable and unreliable models\n",
    "Detect using VIF\n",
    "Fix using feature selection or regularization\n",
    "\n",
    "If you want next, I can give:\n",
    "🔥 \n",
    "VIF calculation with full Python code\n",
    "🔥 \n",
    "Ridge vs Lasso deep comparison\n",
    "🔥 \n",
    "Feature selection techniques (very important for interviews)"
   ]
